{
    "analysis": "The previous step loaded all four CSVs and returned compact summaries. Metric.csv contains 26,775 rows spanning 2021-03-07 03:30 to 2021-03-07 04:00 (UTC+8) and many component-KPI groups (top groups shown). Trace.csv and log.csv were similarly summarized; trace has 2,823 rows and relevant trace groups (IG01, MG01, IG02, Tomcat04, etc.). error_logs.csv is empty. From these summaries, candidate components with rich metric coverage include apache02, IG01, Tomcat04, apache01, Tomcat01, MG01/MG02, Tomcat02/03. We should next run metric-based anomaly detection (using global thresholds) to narrow down faulty component-KPI groups and the earliest anomaly timestamps within the incident window. No fault has been identified yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full metric.csv (no time filtering for threshold calc), do the following and store results in kernel variables:\n1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group compute the global P95 of value and total row count across the entire metric.csv.\n2) Filter metric.csv rows to the incident time window: March 7, 2021 03:30 to 2021-03-07 04:00 (UTC+8) and compute per group within-window statistics: window_count, anomaly_count where anomaly means value >= global P95 (from step 1), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first timestamp in window where value >= P95), max_value_in_window.\n3) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of groups that have anomaly_count>0 sorted by anomaly_count descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_count, p95_value, window_count, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window.\nAlso return the total number of metric groups scanned and the number of groups with anomalies. Keep full intermediate DataFrames cached for follow-up steps but only print the compact table and the two counts."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and trace anomaly scans. Metrics show nearly every KPI across all components exceeded global P95 throughout the window (many groups flagged from 03:30). Component aggregation ranks Mysql02 as the most severe (max_severity=20x) with many affected KPIs and earliest anomalies at 2021-03-07 03:30+08:00. Trace analysis shows widespread high-latency anomalies concentrated around 03:41–03:42+08:00 and some low-traffic hits earlier (~03:32+08:00). Traces implicate services MG01, Tomcat01 and dockerB1 with high latency around 03:41–03:42, but there are no obvious DB trace links in the trace summary. error_logs.csv is empty and log.csv contains only normalized log metrics (error_count mostly 0). Given the extreme severity and breadth of KPI breaches on Mysql02 (20x over P95) starting at 03:30, Mysql02 is a primary candidate root cause, but we need concrete per-KPI anomaly evidence (timestamps and breach magnitude) for Mysql02 to confirm whether its faults are both significant (>50% breach) and earliest relative to other components. Traces show downstream latency later, which could be caused by an earlier DB problem. Next we must extract limited per-KPI anomaly rows for Mysql02 top offending KPIs in the incident window to verify exact earliest occurrence time and severity.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the cached metric DataFrame and the global P95 thresholds (calculated from the full metric.csv), extract details for the top 3 Mysql02 KPI groups by severity (as reported: e.g., Mysql-MySQL_3306_Opened Tables, Mysql-MySQL_3306_Table open cache misses, Mysql-MySQL_3306_Rows Read). For each of these 3 KPI groups do the following:\n1) Filter metric rows to the incident window (2021-03-07 03:30 to 2021-03-07 04:00 UTC+8) and where value >= global P95 for that KPI group.\n2) Return up to the earliest 5 anomaly rows per KPI with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value.\n3) For each KPI group also return its global p95_value, the max_value_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first row from step 2), and a boolean flag 'strong_breach' indicating whether (max_value_in_window / p95_value) > 1.5 (i.e., breach >50%).\nLimit printed output to at most 15 rows (5 per KPI) plus a small summary table listing the three KPIs with their p95_value, max_value_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, and strong_breach. Keep the filtered rows and KPI summary cached for follow-up steps but only print the compact results described."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step inspected the top-3 Mysql02 KPI groups (Opened Tables, Table open cache misses, Rows Read) within the incident window and confirmed strong breaches (max / P95 > 1.5) with example anomaly rows observed at 2021-03-07 03:43:00+08:00. This shows Mysql02 experienced significant MySQL-specific metric spikes at 03:43+08:00. However, earlier component-level aggregation indicated many components (including Mysql02) had KPI anomalies starting at 03:30+08:00 — likely other KPI types (OS/network/disk) — and trace anomalies clustered later around 03:41–03:42+08:00. To localize the root cause we must determine the true earliest anomaly within Mysql02 across all its KPI groups (not just the top-3 by severity) to see whether Mysql02 faults actually began at 03:30 or later at 03:43 and whether the early 03:30 signals point to DB issues or to other underlying resource problems on the host.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the cached metric-group anomaly table (per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) entries with p95_value, window_count, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window), filter to cmdb_id == 'Mysql02' and anomaly_count>0. Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of the Mysql02 KPI groups sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_value, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, severity (max_value_in_window / p95_value). Also return two counts: total Mysql02 KPI groups scanned and number with anomaly_count>0. Keep full filtered DataFrame cached for follow-up steps but only print the compact table and the two counts."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through threshold calculation and anomaly scans. Metric analysis showed nearly every KPI across all 14 candidate components exceeded global P95 during the incident window. Trace analysis found service-level latency spikes concentrated around 03:41–03:42+08:00 and some low-traffic drops around ~03:32+08:00. Focused inspection of Mysql02 revealed (a) many Mysql02 KPIs report anomalies starting at 03:30+08:00, and (b) the highest-severity MySQL-specific KPI spikes (Opened Tables, Table open cache misses, Rows Read) were observed at 03:43+08:00 and are strong breaches. However, there is an ordering ambiguity: many Mysql02 KPIs flagged anomalies at 03:30, while MySQL-specific severe spikes appear at 03:43, and trace latencies began ~03:41–03:42. To identify the root cause component and exact occurrence time we must find the earliest significant (strong) breaches across the allowed components — i.e., KPI breaches that are substantial (max / p95 > 1.5) and earliest in time. This will let us determine which component first experienced a severe fault (root cause candidate) and whether the MySQL severe spikes were primary or secondary. Next step: compute per-component earliest timestamp when any KPI had a strong breach (severity>1.5), count how many such strong KPIs each component had, and the component-level max severity. This will yield a short ranked list of candidate root-cause components and their earliest strong-fault times for cross-checking with traces/logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) anomaly table (which contains p95_value, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, and severity = max_value_in_window / p95_value), restrict to the allowed candidate components list [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02].\n1) Filter KPI groups to those with severity > 1.5 (i.e., max_value_in_window / p95_value > 1.5) to focus on strong breaches.\n2) For each component compute: strong_kpi_count (number of KPI groups with severity>1.5), earliest_strong_anomaly (minimum earliest_anomaly_timestamp among those KPI groups), component_max_severity (maximum severity among those KPI groups).\n3) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of components that have strong_kpi_count>0 sorted by earliest_strong_anomaly ascending with columns: cmdb_id, strong_kpi_count, earliest_strong_anomaly, component_max_severity. Also return two counts: number of components scanned (restricted set) and number of components with strong_kpi_count>0.\nKeep the filtered strong-KPI rows and per-component results cached for follow-up analysis but only print the compact component table and the two counts."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global-threshold calculation and metric anomaly detection, then trace anomaly analysis and component-level aggregation. Key findings so far: (1) Metrics are noisy but nearly every KPI across the 14 candidate components exceeded global P95 during 03:30–04:00. (2) Strong KPI breaches (severity >1.5) exist on all components; IG01 shows earliest strong anomalies at 2021-03-07 03:32:00+08:00, Mysql02 shows many strong KPI breaches (41 KPIs) with very high max severity (20×) and earliest strong anomaly at 2021-03-07 03:33:00+08:00. (3) Traces show service-level high-latency spikes concentrated around 03:41–03:42+08:00 (MG01, Tomcat01, dockerB1 etc.), and some low-traffic row_count drops earlier (~03:32+08:00). (4) Focused inspection of top Mysql02 KPIs found strong MySQL-specific spikes (Opened Tables, Table open cache misses, Rows Read) at 2021-03-07 03:43:00+08:00. There remains an ordering ambiguity: some Mysql02 OS/process-level KPIs flagged anomalies at 03:30, while the most severe MySQL-specific spikes and service-level trace latencies occur later (03:41–03:43). To resolve root cause we need to (A) determine whether traces include DB calls to Mysql02 (to establish DB as upstream/downstream in call chains), and (B) confirm the exact earliest strong anomaly timestamps on Mysql02 across all KPI types to see whether Mysql02 experienced a primary failure before other services' latency spikes or whether MySQL degradation is secondary. Currently we cannot finalize root cause because traces linking to Mysql02 are not yet inspected and logs/error details for Mysql02 are not available.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Search the cached trace DataFrame for any trace groups that reference Mysql02. Specifically, find all (cmdb_id, trace_name) groups where either cmdb_id == 'Mysql02' OR trace_name contains the substring 'Mysql02' OR trace_name contains 'to_Mysql02' OR 'from_Mysql02'. For each matching group compute across the full trace.csv: total_count, global P95 (p95_value), global P5 (p5_value). Then filter to the incident window (2021-03-07 03:30 to 04:00 UTC+8) and compute window_count, anomaly definition (for duration traces: value >= p95_value; for row_count: value <= p5_value), anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of matching groups with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_count, p95_value, p5_value, window_count, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Also return the total number of trace groups scanned and the number of matching groups found. Keep intermediate results cached but only print the compact table and two counts."
}

